=== Example 0 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions, so that the expressions can be evaluated by a theorem solver like Prover9 to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
Expressions should adhere to the format of the Python NLTK package logic module. The output should follow format TEXT: 
FOL: 
TEXT: 
FOL:...


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
FOL: all x. (Biodegradable(x) -> EnvironmentFriendly(x))
TEXT: All woodware is biodegradable.
FOL: all x. (Woodware(x) -> Biodegradable(x))
TEXT: All paper is woodware.
FOL: all x. (Paper(x) -> Woodware(x))
TEXT: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
FOL: -(exists x. (Good(x) & Bad(x)))
TEXT: All environment-friendly things are good.
FOL: all x. (EnvironmentFriendly(x) -> Good(x))
TEXT: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
FOL: ((Paper(Worksheet) & -EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)) | (-Paper(Worksheet) & EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)))
TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) -> SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
FOL: all x. (OlympicGoldMedalWinner(x) -> ProfessionalAthlete(x))
TEXT: No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (FullTimeScientist(x) -> -SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
FOL: all x. (NobelPhysicsLaureate(x) -> FullTimeScientist(x))
TEXT: Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: SpendOn(Amy, MostOfTheirTime, Sports) | OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: -NobelPhysicsLaureate(Amy) -> -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
FOL: -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy) -> NobelLaureate(Amy)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Bonnie performs in school talent shows often.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Generation 1:
TEXT: People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & PerformTalentShow(x) -> (AttendSchoolEvents(x) & Engaged(x)))
TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformTalentShow(x) | (Inactive(x) & Disinterested(x))))
TEXT: People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & ChaperoneDance(x) -> -Student(x))
TEXT: All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & Inactive(x) & Disinterested(x) -> ChaperoneDance(x))
TEXT: All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & Young(x) & WantAcademicCareer(x) -> Student(x))
TEXT: Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
FOL: InClub(Bonnie) & ((AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & Engaged(Bonnie) & Student(Bonnie)) | (-AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -Engaged(Bonnie) & -Student(Bonnie)))
TEXT: Bonnie performs in school talent shows often.
FOL: PerformTalentShow(Bonnie)
Processed: Uncertain

Generation 2:
TEXT: People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & PerformInTalentShows(x) -> AttendAndEngagedWithEvents(x))
TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformInTalentShows(x) | InactiveAndDisinterested(x)))
TEXT: People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & ChaperoneDances(x) -> -Student(x))
TEXT: All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & InactiveAndDisinterested(x) -> ChaperoneDances(x))
TEXT: All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & YoungOrTeen(x) & WantToAdvanceAcademics(x) -> Student(x))
TEXT: Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
FOL: InClub(Bonnie) & ((AttendAndEngagedWithEvents(Bonnie) & Student(Bonnie)) | (-AttendAndEngagedWithEvents(Bonnie) & -Student(Bonnie)))
TEXT: Bonnie performs in school talent shows often.
FOL: PerformInTalentShows(Bonnie)
</EVALUATE>
Processed: Uncertain

Generation 3:
TEXT: People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & PerformInTalentShows(x) -> (AttendAndEngagedWithSchoolEvents(x)))
TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformInTalentShows(x) | (InactiveAndDisinterested(x))))
TEXT: People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(x) -> -StudentAttendSchool(x))
TEXT: All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & InactiveAndDisinterested(x) -> ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(x))
TEXT: All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & YoungChildrenOrTeenagers(x) & WishFurtherAcademicCareers(x) -> StudentAttendSchool(x))
TEXT: Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
FOL: InClub(Bonnie) & ((AttendAndEngagedWithSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & StudentAttendSchool(Bonnie)) | (-AttendAndEngagedWithSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -StudentAttendSchool(Bonnie)))
TEXT: Bonnie performs in school talent shows often.
FOL: PerformInTalentShows(Bonnie)
</EVALUATE>
Processed: Uncertain

Reference: Uncertain
========================================

=== Example 1 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions, so that the expressions can be evaluated by a theorem solver like Prover9 to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
Expressions should adhere to the format of the Python NLTK package logic module. The output should follow format TEXT: 
FOL: 
TEXT: 
FOL:...


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
FOL: all x. (Biodegradable(x) -> EnvironmentFriendly(x))
TEXT: All woodware is biodegradable.
FOL: all x. (Woodware(x) -> Biodegradable(x))
TEXT: All paper is woodware.
FOL: all x. (Paper(x) -> Woodware(x))
TEXT: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
FOL: -(exists x. (Good(x) & Bad(x)))
TEXT: All environment-friendly things are good.
FOL: all x. (EnvironmentFriendly(x) -> Good(x))
TEXT: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
FOL: ((Paper(Worksheet) & -EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)) | (-Paper(Worksheet) & EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)))
TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) -> SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
FOL: all x. (OlympicGoldMedalWinner(x) -> ProfessionalAthlete(x))
TEXT: No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (FullTimeScientist(x) -> -SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
FOL: all x. (NobelPhysicsLaureate(x) -> FullTimeScientist(x))
TEXT: Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: SpendOn(Amy, MostOfTheirTime, Sports) | OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: -NobelPhysicsLaureate(Amy) -> -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
FOL: -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy) -> NobelLaureate(Amy)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Bonnie is either both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and chaperones high school dances or neither is a young child nor teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities, then Bonnie is either a student who attends the school or is an inactive and disinterested member of the community.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Generation 1:
TEXT: People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & PerformTalentShow(x) -> (AttendSchoolEvents(x) & EngagedWithEvents(x)))
TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformTalentShow(x) | (InactiveCommunityMember(x) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(x))))
TEXT: People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(x) -> -StudentAttendSchool(x))
TEXT: All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & InactiveCommunityMember(x) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(x) -> ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(x))
TEXT: All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & YoungChildOrTeenager(x) & WishFurtherEducation(x) -> StudentAttendSchool(x))
TEXT: Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
FOL: InClub(Bonnie) & ((AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & EngagedWithEvents(Bonnie) & StudentAttendSchool(Bonnie)) | (-AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -EngagedWithEvents(Bonnie) & -StudentAttendSchool(Bonnie)))
TEXT: If Bonnie is either both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and chaperones high school dances or neither is a young child nor teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities, then Bonnie is either a student who attends the school or is an inactive and disinterested member of the community.
FOL: ((YoungChildOrTeenager(Bonnie) & WishFurtherEducation(Bonnie) & ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(Bonnie)) | (-YoungChildOrTeenager(Bonnie) & -WishFurtherEducation(Bonnie))) -> (StudentAttendSchool(Bonnie) | (InactiveCommunityMember(Bonnie) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(Bonnie)))
Processed: True

Generation 2:
TEXT: People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & PerformInSchoolTalentShows(x) -> (AttendSchoolEvents(x) & VeryEngagedWithSchoolEvents(x)))
TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformInSchoolTalentShows(x) | (Inactive(x) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(x))))
TEXT: People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(x) -> -StudentWhoAttendsSchool(x))
TEXT: All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & Inactive(x) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(x) -> ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(x))
TEXT: All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & YoungChildOrTeenager(x) & WishFurtherAcademicCareer(x) -> StudentWhoAttendsSchool(x))
TEXT: Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
FOL: InClub(Bonnie) & ((AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & VeryEngagedWithSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & StudentWhoAttendsSchool(Bonnie)) | (-AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -VeryEngagedWithSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -StudentWhoAttendsSchool(Bonnie)))
TEXT: If Bonnie is either both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and chaperones high school dances or neither is a young child nor teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities, then Bonnie is either a student who attends the school or is an inactive and disinterested member of the community.
FOL: ((YoungChildOrTeenager(Bonnie) & WishFurtherAcademicCareer(Bonnie) & ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(Bonnie)) | (-YoungChildOrTeenager(Bonnie) & -WishFurtherAcademicCareer(Bonnie))) -> (StudentWhoAttendsSchool(Bonnie) | (Inactive(Bonnie) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(Bonnie)))
Processed: True

Generation 3:
TEXT: People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & PerformTalentShow(x) -> (AttendSchoolEvents(x) & EngagedWithSchoolEvents(x)))

TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformTalentShow(x) | (InactiveCommunityMember(x) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(x))))

TEXT: People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & ChaperoneDances(x) -> -Student(x))

TEXT: All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & InactiveCommunityMember(x) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(x) -> ChaperoneDances(x))

TEXT: All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & YoungOrTeenager(x) & WishFurtherEducation(x) -> Student(x))

TEXT: Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
FOL: InClub(Bonnie) & ((AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & EngagedWithSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & Student(Bonnie)) | (-AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -EngagedWithSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -Student(Bonnie)))

TEXT: If Bonnie is either both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and chaperones high school dances or neither is a young child nor teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities, then Bonnie is either a student who attends the school or is an inactive and disinterested member of the community.
FOL: ((YoungOrTeenager(Bonnie) & WishFurtherEducation(Bonnie) & ChaperoneDances(Bonnie)) | (-YoungOrTeenager(Bonnie) & -WishFurtherEducation(Bonnie))) -> (Student(Bonnie) | (InactiveCommunityMember(Bonnie) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(Bonnie)))
</EVALUATE>
Processed: True

Reference: True

=== Example 2 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions, so that the expressions can be evaluated by a theorem solver like Prover9 to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
Expressions should adhere to the format of the Python NLTK package logic module. The output should follow format TEXT: 
FOL: 
TEXT: 
FOL:...


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
FOL: all x. (Biodegradable(x) -> EnvironmentFriendly(x))
TEXT: All woodware is biodegradable.
FOL: all x. (Woodware(x) -> Biodegradable(x))
TEXT: All paper is woodware.
FOL: all x. (Paper(x) -> Woodware(x))
TEXT: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
FOL: -(exists x. (Good(x) & Bad(x)))
TEXT: All environment-friendly things are good.
FOL: all x. (EnvironmentFriendly(x) -> Good(x))
TEXT: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
FOL: ((Paper(Worksheet) & -EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)) | (-Paper(Worksheet) & EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)))
TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) -> SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
FOL: all x. (OlympicGoldMedalWinner(x) -> ProfessionalAthlete(x))
TEXT: No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (FullTimeScientist(x) -> -SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
FOL: all x. (NobelPhysicsLaureate(x) -> FullTimeScientist(x))
TEXT: Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: SpendOn(Amy, MostOfTheirTime, Sports) | OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: -NobelPhysicsLaureate(Amy) -> -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
FOL: -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy) -> NobelLaureate(Amy)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Bonnie either chaperones high school dances or, if she does not, she performs in school talent shows often, then Bonnie is both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and an inactive and disinterested member of the community.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Generation 1:
TEXT: People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & PerformTalentShows(x) -> (AttendSchoolEvents(x) & EngagedWithSchoolEvents(x)))
TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformTalentShows(x) | (Inactive(x) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(x))))
TEXT: People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(x) -> -StudentWhoAttendsSchool(x))
TEXT: All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & Inactive(x) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(x) -> ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(x))
TEXT: All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & YoungOrTeenager(x) & WishToFurtherAcademicCareer(x) -> StudentWhoAttendsSchool(x))
TEXT: Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
FOL: InClub(Bonnie) & ((AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & EngagedWithSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & StudentWhoAttendsSchool(Bonnie)) | (-AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -EngagedWithSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -StudentWhoAttendsSchool(Bonnie)))
TEXT: If Bonnie either chaperones high school dances or, if she does not, she performs in school talent shows often, then Bonnie is both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and an inactive and disinterested member of the community.
FOL: ((ChaperoneHighSchoolDances(Bonnie) | PerformTalentShows(Bonnie)) -> (YoungOrTeenager(Bonnie) & WishToFurtherAcademicCareer(Bonnie) & Inactive(Bonnie) & DisinterestedCommunityMember(Bonnie)))
Processed: False

Generation 2:
TEXT: People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.

TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformTalentShow(x) | (Inactive(x) & Disinterested(x))))

TEXT: People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & ChaperoneDances(x) -> -Student(x))

TEXT: All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & Inactive(x) & Disinterested(x) -> ChaperoneDances(x))

TEXT: All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) & YoungOrTeen(x) & WishAcademicCareer(x) -> Student(x))

TEXT: Bonnie is in this club and she either both attends and is very engaged with school events and is a student who attends the school or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events and is not a student who attends the school.
FOL: InClub(Bonnie) & ((AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & EngagedWithEvents(Bonnie) & Student(Bonnie)) | (-AttendSchoolEvents(Bonnie) & -EngagedWithEvents(Bonnie) & -Student(Bonnie)))

Processed: False

TEXT: People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.
FOL: all x. (InClub(x) -> (PerformTalentShows(x) | (Inactive(x) & Disinterested(x))))

Processed: False

=== Example 3 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions, so that the expressions can be evaluated by a theorem solver like Prover9 to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
Expressions should adhere to the format of the Python NLTK package logic module. The output should follow format TEXT: 
FOL: 
TEXT: 
FOL:...


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
FOL: all x. (Biodegradable(x) -> EnvironmentFriendly(x))
TEXT: All woodware is biodegradable.
FOL: all x. (Woodware(x) -> Biodegradable(x))
TEXT: All paper is woodware.
FOL: all x. (Paper(x) -> Woodware(x))
TEXT: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
FOL: -(exists x. (Good(x) & Bad(x)))
TEXT: All environment-friendly things are good.
FOL: all x. (EnvironmentFriendly(x) -> Good(x))
TEXT: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
FOL: ((Paper(Worksheet) & -EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)) | (-Paper(Worksheet) & EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)))
TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) -> SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
FOL: all x. (OlympicGoldMedalWinner(x) -> ProfessionalAthlete(x))
TEXT: No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (FullTimeScientist(x) -> -SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
FOL: all x. (NobelPhysicsLaureate(x) -> FullTimeScientist(x))
TEXT: Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: SpendOn(Amy, MostOfTheirTime, Sports) | OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: -NobelPhysicsLaureate(Amy) -> -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
FOL: -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy) -> NobelLaureate(Amy)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All employees who schedule a meeting with their customers will go to the company building today.
Everyone who has lunch in the company building schedules meetings with their customers.
Employees have lunch either in the company building or at home.
If an employee has lunch at home, they are working remotely from home.
All employees who are in other countries work remotely from home.
No managers work remotely from home.
James will appear in the company today if and only if he is a manager.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
James has lunch in the company.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Generation 1:
TEXT: All employees who schedule a meeting with their customers will go to the company building today.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & ScheduleMeetingWithCustomer(x) -> GoToCompanyBuilding(x))
TEXT: Everyone who has lunch in the company building schedules meetings with their customers.
FOL: all x. (LunchInCompanyBuilding(x) -> ScheduleMeetingWithCustomer(x))
TEXT: Employees have lunch either in the company building or at home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) -> (LunchInCompanyBuilding(x) | LunchAtHome(x)))
TEXT: If an employee has lunch at home, they are working remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & LunchAtHome(x) -> WorkingRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: All employees who are in other countries work remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & InOtherCountry(x) -> WorkingRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: No managers work remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Manager(x) -> -WorkingRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: James will appear in the company today if and only if he is a manager.
FOL: AppearInCompanyToday(James) <-> Manager(James)
TEXT: James has lunch in the company.
FOL: LunchInCompanyBuilding(James)
</EVALUATE>
Processed: Uncertain

Generation 2:
TEXT: All employees who schedule a meeting with their customers will go to the company building today.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & ScheduleMeetingWithCustomer(x) -> GoToCompanyBuildingToday(x))
TEXT: Everyone who has lunch in the company building schedules meetings with their customers.
FOL: all x. (HasLunch(x, CompanyBuilding) -> ScheduleMeetingWithCustomer(x))
TEXT: Employees have lunch either in the company building or at home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) -> (HasLunch(x, CompanyBuilding) | HasLunch(x, Home)))
TEXT: If an employee has lunch at home, they are working remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & HasLunch(x, Home) -> WorkRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: All employees who are in other countries work remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & InOtherCountry(x) -> WorkRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: No managers work remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Manager(x) -> -WorkRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: James will appear in the company today if and only if he is a manager.
FOL: AppearInCompanyToday(James) <-> Manager(James)
TEXT: James has lunch in the company.
FOL: HasLunch(James, CompanyBuilding)
</EVALUATE>
Processed: Uncertain

Generation 3:
TEXT: All employees who schedule a meeting with their customers will go to the company building today.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & ScheduleMeetingWithCustomer(x) -> GoToCompanyBuilding(x))
TEXT: Everyone who has lunch in the company building schedules meetings with their customers.
FOL: all x. (HaveLunch(x, CompanyBuilding) -> ScheduleMeetingWithCustomer(x))
TEXT: Employees have lunch either in the company building or at home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) -> (HaveLunch(x, CompanyBuilding) | HaveLunch(x, Home)))
TEXT: If an employee has lunch at home, they are working remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & HaveLunch(x, Home) -> WorkRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: All employees who are in other countries work remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & InOtherCountry(x) -> WorkRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: No managers work remotely from home.

</CONCLUSION>

TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) -> SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
FOL: all x. (OlympicGoldMedalWinner(x) -> ProfessionalAthlete(x))
TEXT: No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (FullTimeScientist(x) -> -SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
FOL: all x. (NobelPhysicsLaureate(x) -> FullTimeScientist(x))
TEXT: Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: SpendOn(Amy, MostOfTheirTime, Sports) | OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: -NobelPhysicsLaureate(Amy) -> -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
FOL: -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy) -> NobelLaureate(Amy)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All employees who schedule a meeting with their customers will go to the company building today.
Everyone who has lunch in the company building schedules meetings with their customers.
Employees have lunch either in the company building or at home.
If an employee has lunch at home, they are working remotely from home.
All employees who are in other countries work remotely from home.
No managers work remotely from home.
James will appear in the company today if and only if he is a manager.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If James is either a manager or in other countries,  then James does not either has lunch at home or work remotely from home. If James either has lunch at home or works remotely from home, then he is neither a manager nor does he work in other countries. [contrapositive is more natural]
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Generation 1:
TEXT: All employees who schedule a meeting with their customers will go to the company building today.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & ScheduleMeetingWithCustomer(x) -> GoToCompanyBuildingToday(x))
TEXT: Everyone who has lunch in the company building schedules meetings with their customers.
FOL: all x. (HasLunchInCompanyBuilding(x) -> ScheduleMeetingWithCustomer(x))
TEXT: Employees have lunch either in the company building or at home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) -> (HasLunchInCompanyBuilding(x) | HasLunchAtHome(x)))
TEXT: If an employee has lunch at home, they are working remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & HasLunchAtHome(x) -> WorkingRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: All employees who are in other countries work remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & InOtherCountries(x) -> WorkingRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: No managers work remotely from home.
FOL: all x. (Manager(x) -> -WorkingRemotelyFromHome(x))
TEXT: James will appear in the company today if and only if he is a manager.
FOL: AppearInCompanyToday(James) <-> Manager(James)
TEXT: If James is either a manager or in other countries, then James does not either have lunch at home or work remotely from home.
FOL: (Manager(James) | InOtherCountries(James)) -> -(HasLunchAtHome(James) | WorkingRemotelyFromHome(James))
TEXT: If James either has lunch at home or works remotely from home, then he is neither a manager nor does he work in other countries.
FOL: (HasLunchAtHome(James) | WorkingRemotelyFromHome(James)) -> (-Manager(James) & -InOtherCountries(James))
Processed: True

Generation 2:
TEXT: All employees who schedule a meeting with their customers will go to the company building today.
FOL: all x. (Employee(x) & ScheduleMeeting(x, Customer(x)) -> GoToCompanyBuilding(x, today))

FOL: all x. (LunchInCompanyBuilding(x) -> ScheduleMeeting(x, Customer(x)))

FOL: (LunchAtHome(James) | WorkRemotelyFromHome(James)) -> (-Manager(James) & -InOtherCountries(James))
Processed: True

=== Example 6 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions, so that the expressions can be evaluated by a theorem solver like Prover9 to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
Expressions should adhere to the format of the Python NLTK package logic module. The output should follow format TEXT: 
FOL: 
TEXT: 
FOL:...


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
FOL: all x. (Biodegradable(x) -> EnvironmentFriendly(x))
TEXT: All woodware is biodegradable.
FOL: all x. (Woodware(x) -> Biodegradable(x))
TEXT: All paper is woodware.
FOL: all x. (Paper(x) -> Woodware(x))
TEXT: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
FOL: -(exists x. (Good(x) & Bad(x)))
TEXT: All environment-friendly things are good.
FOL: all x. (EnvironmentFriendly(x) -> Good(x))
TEXT: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
FOL: ((Paper(Worksheet) & -EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)) | (-Paper(Worksheet) & EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)))
TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) -> SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
FOL: all x. (OlympicGoldMedalWinner(x) -> ProfessionalAthlete(x))
TEXT: No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.

FOL: all x. (NobelPhysicsLaureate(x) -> FullTimeScientist(x))

FOL: SpendOn(Amy, MostOfTheirTime, Sports) | OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: -NobelPhysicsLaureate(Amy) -> -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
FOL: -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy) -> NobelLaureate(Amy)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
When the Monkeypox virus occurs in a being, it may get Monkeypox.
Monkeypox virus can occur in certain animals.
Humans are mammals.
Mammals are animals.
Symptoms of Monkeypox include fever, headache, muscle pains, and tiredness.
People feel tired when they get the flu.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
There is an animal.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Generation 1:
TEXT: When the Monkeypox virus occurs in a being, it may get Monkeypox.
FOL: all x. (MonkeypoxVirusOccursIn(x) -> MayGetMonkeypox(x))
TEXT: Monkeypox virus can occur in certain animals.
FOL: exists x. (Animal(x) & MonkeypoxVirusOccursIn(x))
TEXT: Humans are mammals.
FOL: all x. (Human(x) -> Mammal(x))
TEXT: Mammals are animals.
FOL: all x. (Mammal(x) -> Animal(x))
TEXT: Symptoms of Monkeypox include fever, headache, muscle pains, and tiredness.
FOL: all x. (Monkeypox(x) -> (Fever(x) & Headache(x) & MusclePains(x) & Tiredness(x)))
TEXT: People feel tired when they get the flu.
FOL: all x. (Person(x) & Flu(x) -> Tired(x))
TEXT: There is an animal.
FOL: exists x. Animal(x)
</EVALUATE>
Processed: True

Generation 2:
TEXT: When the Monkeypox virus occurs in a being, it may get Monkeypox.
FOL: all x. (MonkeypoxVirusOccursIn(x) -> MayGetMonkeypox(x))
TEXT: Monkeypox virus can occur in certain animals.
FOL: exists x. (Animal(x) & MonkeypoxVirusOccursIn(x))
TEXT: Humans are mammals.
FOL: all x. (Human(x) -> Mammal(x))
TEXT: Mammals are animals.
FOL: all x. (Mammal(x) -> Animal(x))
TEXT: Symptoms of Monkeypox include fever, headache, muscle pains, and tiredness.
FOL: all x. (Monkeypox(x) -> (Fever(x) & Headache(x) & MusclePains(x) & Tiredness(x)))
TEXT: People feel tired when they get the flu.
FOL: all x. (Person(x) & HasFlu(x) -> Tiredness(x))
TEXT: There is an animal.
FOL: exists x. Animal(x)
Processed: True

Generation 3:
TEXT: When the Monkeypox virus occurs in a being, it may get Monkeypox.
FOL: all x. (OccursIn(x, MonkeypoxVirus) -> MayGet(x, Monkeypox))
TEXT: Monkeypox virus can occur in certain animals.
FOL: exists x. (Animal(x) & OccursIn(x, MonkeypoxVirus))
TEXT: Humans are mammals.
FOL: all x. (Human(x) -> Mammal(x))
TEXT: Mammals are animals.
FOL: all x. (Mammal(x) -> Animal(x))
TEXT: Symptoms of Monkeypox include fever, headache, muscle pains, and tiredness.
FOL: all x. (Monkeypox(x) -> HasSymptoms(x, [Fever, Headache, MusclePains, Tiredness]))
TEXT: People feel tired when they get the flu.
FOL: all x. (Human(x) & HasFlu(x) -> Feels(x, Tiredness))
TEXT: There is an animal.
FOL: exists x. Animal(x)
Processed: Error

Reference: True

=== Example 9 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions, so that the expressions can be evaluated by a theorem solver like Prover9 to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
Expressions should adhere to the format of the Python NLTK package logic module. The output should follow format TEXT: 
FOL: 
TEXT: 
FOL:...


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
FOL: all x. (Biodegradable(x) -> EnvironmentFriendly(x))
TEXT: All woodware is biodegradable.
FOL: all x. (Woodware(x) -> Biodegradable(x))
TEXT: All paper is woodware.
FOL: all x. (Paper(x) -> Woodware(x))
TEXT: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
FOL: -(exists x. (Good(x) & Bad(x)))
TEXT: All environment-friendly things are good.
FOL: all x. (EnvironmentFriendly(x) -> Good(x))
TEXT: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
FOL: ((Paper(Worksheet) & -EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)) | (-Paper(Worksheet) & EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)))
TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

=== Example 12 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions, so that the expressions can be evaluated by a theorem solver like Prover9 to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
Expressions should adhere to the format of the Python NLTK package logic module. The output should follow format TEXT: 
FOL: 
TEXT: 
FOL:...


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
FOL: all x. (Biodegradable(x) -> EnvironmentFriendly(x))
TEXT: All woodware is biodegradable.
FOL: all x. (Woodware(x) -> Biodegradable(x))
TEXT: All paper is woodware.
FOL: all x. (Paper(x) -> Woodware(x))
TEXT: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
FOL: -(exists x. (Good(x) & Bad(x)))
TEXT: All environment-friendly things are good.
FOL: all x. (EnvironmentFriendly(x) -> Good(x))
TEXT: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
FOL: ((Paper(Worksheet) & -EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)) | (-Paper(Worksheet) & EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)))
TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) -> SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
FOL: all x. (OlympicGoldMedalWinner(x) -> ProfessionalAthlete(x))
TEXT: No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (FullTimeScientist(x) -> -SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.

FOL: SpendOn(Amy, MostOfTheirTime, Sports) | OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: -NobelPhysicsLaureate(Amy) -> -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
FOL: -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy) -> NobelLaureate(Amy)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>

All games on the Top 10 list are made by Japanese game companies.
If a game sells more than one million copies, then it will be included in the Top 10 list.

TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>

=== Example 16 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions, so that the expressions can be evaluated by a theorem solver like Prover9 to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
Expressions should adhere to the format of the Python NLTK package logic module. The output should follow format TEXT: 
FOL: 
TEXT: 
FOL:...


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
FOL: all x. (Biodegradable(x) -> EnvironmentFriendly(x))
TEXT: All woodware is biodegradable.
FOL: all x. (Woodware(x) -> Biodegradable(x))
TEXT: All paper is woodware.
FOL: all x. (Paper(x) -> Woodware(x))
TEXT: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
FOL: -(exists x. (Good(x) & Bad(x)))
TEXT: All environment-friendly things are good.
FOL: all x. (EnvironmentFriendly(x) -> Good(x))
TEXT: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
FOL: ((Paper(Worksheet) & -EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)) | (-Paper(Worksheet) & EnvironmentFriendly(Worksheet)))
TEXT: A worksheet is not biodegradable.
FOL: -Dispensable(Worksheet)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & MorePoints(x, y) -> RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
FOL: all x. all y. (LaLigaSoccerTeam(x) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(y) & -MorePoints(x, y) & -MorePoints(y, x) & MorePointsInGameBetween(x, y) ->  RankHigherThan(x, y))
TEXT: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
FOL: LaLigaSoccerTeam(RealMadrid) & LaLigaSoccerTeam(Barcelona)
TEXT: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
FOL: MorePoints(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
TEXT: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
FOL: -MorePointsInGameBetween(RealMadrid, Barcelona) & -MorePointsInGameBetween(Barcelona, RealMadrid)
TEXT: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
FOL: HigherRank(RealMadrid, Barcelona)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
TEXT: All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) -> SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
FOL: all x. (OlympicGoldMedalWinner(x) -> ProfessionalAthlete(x))
TEXT: No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
FOL: all x. (FullTimeScientist(x) -> -SpendOn(x, MostOfTheirTime, Sports))
TEXT: All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
FOL: all x. (NobelPhysicsLaureate(x) -> FullTimeScientist(x))
TEXT: Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: SpendOn(Amy, MostOfTheirTime, Sports) | OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
FOL: -NobelPhysicsLaureate(Amy) -> -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy)
TEXT: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
FOL: -OlympicGoldMedalWinner(Amy) -> NobelLaureate(Amy)
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All rabbits that can be spotted near the campus are cute.
Some turtles can be spotted near the campus.
The only animals that can be spotted near the campus are rabbits and squirrels.
If something is skittish, then it is not calm.
All the squirrels that can be spotted near the campus are skittish.
Rockie can be spotted near the campus, and it is calm.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Rockie is a turtle.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Generation 1:
TEXT: All rabbits that can be spotted near the campus are cute.
FOL: all x. (Rabbit(x) & CanBeSpottedNearCampus(x) -> Cute(x))
TEXT: Some turtles can be spotted near the campus.
FOL: exists x. (Turtle(x) & CanBeSpottedNearCampus(x))
TEXT: The only animals that can be spotted near the campus are rabbits and squirrels.
FOL: all x. (CanBeSpottedNearCampus(x) -> (Rabbit(x) | Squirrel(x)))
TEXT: If something is skittish, then it is not calm.
FOL: all x. (Skittish(x) -> -Calm(x))
TEXT: All the squirrels that can be spotted near the campus are skittish.
FOL: all x. (Squirrel(x) & CanBeSpottedNearCampus(x) -> Skittish(x))
TEXT: Rockie can be spotted near the campus, and it is calm.
FOL: CanBeSpottedNearCampus(Rockie) & Calm(Rockie)
TEXT: Rockie is a turtle.
FOL: Turtle(Rockie)
Processed: Uncertain

Generation 2:
TEXT: All rabbits that can be spotted near the campus are cute.
FOL: all x. (Rabbit(x) & CanBeSpottedNearCampus(x) -> Cute(x))
TEXT: Some turtles can be spotted near the campus.
FOL: exists x. (Turtle(x) & CanBeSpottedNearCampus(x))
TEXT: The only animals that can be spotted near the campus are rabbits and squirrels.
FOL: all x. (CanBeSpottedNearCampus(x) -> (Rabbit(x) | Squirrel(x)))
TEXT: If something is skittish, then it is not calm.
FOL: all x. (Skittish(x) -> -Calm(x))
TEXT: All the squirrels that can be spotted near the campus are skittish.
FOL: all x. (Squirrel(x) & CanBeSpottedNearCampus(x) -> Skittish(x))
TEXT: Rockie can be spotted near the campus, and it is calm.
FOL: CanBeSpottedNearCampus(Rockie) & Calm(Rockie)
TEXT: Rockie is a turtle.
FOL: Turtle(Rockie)
Processed: Uncertain

Generation 3:
TEXT: All rabbits that can be spotted near the campus are cute.
FOL: all x. (Rabbit(x) & SpottedNearCampus(x) -> Cute(x))
TEXT: Some turtles can be spotted near the campus.
FOL: exists x. (Turtle(x) & SpottedNearCampus(x))
